	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Increased use of refrigerated containers opens alternate supply opportunities for banana exporters</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>An article published on the Maersk shipping line’s website has described the change under way in the transportation of bananas resulting from the increase in the use of refrigerated containers, known as ‘reefer containers’. A single 20-foot container can hold 48,000 bananas. Significantly, the use of refrigerated containers allows bananas to be kept fresh for up to 50 days, creating new marketing opportunities. Already in 2009 around a third of all bananas were transported internationally in refrigerated containers, and this proportion is growing.</p><p>According to a Maersk Line in-house study on the Indian banana trade, ‘refrigerated containers can support smallholder growers in getting their bananas to foreign markets at a higher value than they can achieve domestically and at much lower waste levels’. It is also noted that ‘the modular nature of refrigerated containers means smallholder farmers are more easily able to distribute smaller volumes.’ This is seen as opening up new opportunities for ‘more inclusive’ supply chains.</p><p>The Maersk Line article also highlights the findings of a study by WWF/UN Global Compact on ‘Smart Goods Transport’ that growing certain products, e.g. in Africa, and shipping them to Europe in energy-efficient vessels can be less carbon-intensive than greenhouse production in Europe. Maersk adds that, in response to consumer concerns, it has recently joined a multi-stakeholder alliance ‘to advance key economic, social and environmental objectives in global food supply chains’.</p><p>However, an article posted on <i>Freshplaza.com</i> reports that research undertaken by the South African Citrus Growers Association has suggested that pallets used in ‘reefer containers’ are 15% heavier than conventional pallets, with consequent cost implications along the logistics chain, while the incidence of damage to citrus fruits was reportedly higher (based on off-the-record comments from cargo insurers).</p><p>A focus of the Maersk article was on the scope for expanding imports of bananas from India, the world’s largest banana producer. Press reports indicate that Brazil is also to initiate a major banana export drive from the second half of 2012, following the elaboration of ‘good practice’ protocols for the production of export-quality bananas. The first scheduled exports to the EU are set for November 2012, and there are hopes that Germany in particular will offer considerable market potential for the ‘silver banana’ variety.</p><p>Ecuador, meanwhile, is increasingly concerned about the rise of Guatemala and Peru as banana exporters, according to another article posted on Freshplaza.com. Guatemala has high productivity levels (3,500 boxes per ha, compared to 1,800/ha in Ecuador), and Peru has a specialist focus on organic banana production. Peruvian organic banana exports in the first quarter of 2012 were reportedly up 30% compared to the same period in 2011, which was itself a record year.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Maersk Line, ‘Maersk Line goes bananas ...’, 6 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.maerskline.com/link/?page=news&amp;path=/news/story_page/12/Maersk_banana" target="_blank">http://www.maerskline.com/link/?page=news&amp;path=/news/story_page/12/M...</a></p><p>360 Quality Association, ‘Less chance of damage to fresh produce shipped in containers?’, 29 May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=96854#SlideFrame_1" target="_blank">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=96854#SlideFrame_1</a></p><p><i>Freshplaza.com</i>, ‘Brazil expects to export large amounts of banana’, 16 April 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=95300#SlideFrame_1" target="_blank">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=95300#SlideFrame_1</a></p><p><i>Freshplaza.com</i>, ‘Guatemala and Peru, are threats to banana industry’, 28 May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=96786#SlideFrame_1" target="_blank">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=96786#SlideFrame_1</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>A revolution in the shipping of bananas is currently taking place. The traditional fleet controlled by the vertically integrated banana multinationals declined by 8% between 2000 and 2008, but has accelerated since 2008 by up to 19% (2008–2011). This period has coincided with the rise of ‘reefer containers’ capable of delivering high-quality bananas to retailers, and a growing number of EU retailers are exploring the direct purchasing of bananas from producers, circumventing the traditional supply chains. Symptomatic of this was the report in November 2011 of the start of exports of bananas from Panama direct to the Spanish supermarket Mercadona. Although the volumes directly exported by Panamanian producers are small at present, Mercadona purchases 30 million kg of bananas and 10 million kg of plantains yearly.&nbsp;</p><p>This change in the shipping of bananas potentially presents new opportunities for traditional ACP banana suppliers to get closer to the final customer, allowing the strategic repositioning of ACP suppliers within banana supply chains serving the EU market and beyond. This is particularly the case for specialist suppliers such as Windward Island fair-trade producers or Dominican Republic organic banana exporters, who would be able to identify and deal with key market outlets.</p><p>However, the opportunity is equally open to non-ACP banana exporters. The emergence of India as a potential major source of supply, the expansion of Brazilian exports and the growing focus of Peru on organic banana production all pose threats to ACP banana suppliers.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
